 :tx/rationale "SCALING ANALYSIS: Current daemon is single-threaded synchronous (daemon.rs:1016 handle_connection blocks accept loop). At N concurrent agents with R requests/agent/second: (1) Throughput ceiling = 1/latency_per_request. Status takes ~3s → ceiling = 0.3 req/s. Even with sub-100ms daemon responses, ceiling = 10 req/s. (2) At 100 agents × 1 req/10s = 10 req/s → at ceiling. At 100 agents × 1 req/s = 100 req/s → 10x over ceiling. (3) DW0b flush guard under flock: list_tx_hashes is O(F) where F=13K files = ~10ms under exclusive lock. At 100 concurrent direct-mode processes, flock contention = 100 × 10ms = 1s of serialized waiting. ASUPERSYNC INSIGHT: The two-phase reserve/commit pattern + sharded state + RwLock concurrency model solves all three bottlenecks. For braid: (A) Multi-threaded daemon with RwLock<Store> — reads (status, query) take shared lock (unlimited concurrency), writes (observe, task) take exclusive lock (serialized but fast). (B) Replace per-txn .edn files with Write-Ahead Log — single append-only file with O(1) append vs O(F) directory listing. (C) Two-phase write_tx: reserve TxId (lock-free atomic increment) → build datoms → commit (brief exclusive lock for Store::apply_datoms). This separates the expensive part (datom construction) from the critical section (store update)."
